hands_on_practices.solution:
We are asked to change the matrix representation of the density operator from the computational basis $\{|0\rangle,|1\rangle\}$ to the $\{|+\rangle,|-\rangle\}$ basis. The general rule for changing the matrix representation of an operator under a basis change is that if the columns of $S$ are the new basis vectors expressed in the old basis, then
$$
\rho_{\text{new}} = S^{\dagger} \rho_{\text{old}} S.
$$
Here, the new basis vectors are
$$
|+\rangle = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 1\end{pmatrix}, \quad
|-\rangle = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\begin{pmatrix}1 \\ -1\end{pmatrix},
$$
so the change-of-basis matrix (columns are $|+\rangle$ and $|-\rangle$ in the old basis) is
$$
S = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
1 & -1
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
This matrix is unitary and Hermitian, so $S^{\dagger} = S$. Therefore the density matrix in the $\{|+\rangle,|-\rangle\}$ basis is
$$
\rho_{x} = S \rho_{z} S.
$$

Compute the product $\rho_{z} S$ first:
$$
\rho_{z} S = 
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{3}{4} & \frac{1 - i}{4} \\
\frac{1 + i}{4} & \frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}
\cdot
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
1 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{3}{4} + \frac{1 - i}{4} & \frac{3}{4} - \frac{1 - i}{4} \\
\frac{1 + i}{4} + \frac{1}{4} & \frac{1 + i}{4} - \frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Evaluating each entry:
- $(1,1)$: $\frac{3}{4} + \frac{1 - i}{4} = 1 - \frac{i}{4}$,
- $(1,2)$: $\frac{3}{4} - \frac{1 - i}{4} = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4}$,
- $(2,1)$: $\frac{1 + i}{4} + \frac{1}{4} = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4}$,
- $(2,2)$: $\frac{1 + i}{4} - \frac{1}{4} = \frac{i}{4}$,
so
$$
\rho_{z} S = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 - \frac{i}{4} & \frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4} \\
\frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4} & \frac{i}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$

Now multiply on the left by $S$:
$$
\rho_{x} = S (\rho_{z} S) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
1 & -1
\end{pmatrix}
\cdot
\left[
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 - \frac{i}{4} & \frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4} \\
\frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{4} & \frac{i}{4}
\end{pmatrix}
\right]
= \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{3}{2} & \frac{1}{2} + \frac{i}{2} \\
\frac{1}{2} - \frac{i}{2} & \frac{1}{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Finally,
$$
\rho_{x} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{3}{4} & \frac{1}{4} + \frac{i}{4} \\
\frac{1}{4} - \frac{i}{4} & \frac{1}{4}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$

As a consistency check, $\mathrm{Tr}(\rho_{x}) = \frac{3}{4} + \frac{1}{4} = 1$, and $\rho_{x}$ is Hermitian with nonnegative determinant $\frac{1}{16}$, so it is a valid density matrix.
